The national disaster risk management framework referred to in subsection (1) aims at incorporating the following principles and strategic objectives into disaster risk management planning:
* integrated strategies involving multi stakeholder participation;
* timely disaster risk reduction actions that contribute to sustainable developmentbylimitingthelossoflife and livelihood and environmental and property damage;
* the adequate allocation of resources to regional and local government to ensure that the most vulnerable communities can depend on reliable disaster risk management services;
* the introduction of creative formal and informal initiatives that encourage risk avoidance behaviour on the part of individuals, the private sector and government;
* the introduction of mechanisms to ensure that Namibiaâs transportation, critical services such as telecommunications, electricity and public sector infrastructure networks are able to withstand potential threats;
* the introduction of mechanisms for setting and implementing minimum building standards, especially for low-cost housing, to ensure structural soundness that withstands the impact of extreme weather patterns or other adverse conditions; and
* strategies to ensure that the development of marginal and environmental fragile areas is appropriate and properly planned.
* is based on the national disaster risk management framework;
* is a composite plan comprising all the disaster risk management plans developed for Namibia;
* must contain such other matters as may be prescribed; and
* must be distributed to all relevant stakeholders in disaster risk management.

